\nThe existing godoc does describe the mutation, so this is minor. The pattern is safe because `state` is always a pointer to a mutable struct that gets saved later via `saveSessionState`.\n\n### 2. Copy-paste boilerplate across 3 hooks call sites\n\n**Severity: Medium**\n\nThe three call sites in `manual_commit_hooks.go` follow an almost identical pattern:\n\n```go\n// hasNewTranscriptWork (line 1490)\nif _, resolveErr := resolveTranscriptPath(state); resolveErr != nil {\n    logging.Debug(logCtx, \"hasNewTranscriptWork: transcript path resolution failed\", ...)\n    return false\n}\n\n// extractModifiedFilesFromLiveTranscript (line 1559)\nif _, resolveErr := resolveTranscriptPath(state); resolveErr != nil {\n    logging.Debug(logCtx, \"extractModifiedFilesFromLiveTranscript: transcript path resolution failed\", ...)\n    return nil\n}\n\n// finalizeAllTurnCheckpoints (line 2191)\ntranscriptPath, resolveErr := resolveTranscriptPath(state)\nif resolveErr != nil {\n    logging.Warn(logCtx, \"finalize: transcript path resolution failed, skipping\", ...)\n    state.TurnCheckpointIDs = nil\n    return 1\n}\n```\n\nThese share the same resolve-log-bail structure but differ in:\n- Log message prefix (function name)\n- Log level (Debug vs Warn)\n- Return value type (bool vs []string vs int)\n- Side-effect cleanup (`state.TurnCheckpointIDs = nil` in finalize)\n\nThe differences are meaningful enough that a single wrapper would need to accept callbacks or generics, which would arguably be worse. But the resolve+guard-check pair (resolve path, check empty path, resolve agent, call `GetByAgentType`) is duplicated between `resolveTranscriptPath` and the callers -- both `hasNewTranscriptWork` and `extractModifiedFilesFromLiveTranscript` call `agent.GetByAgentType(state.AgentType)` immediately after resolving, repeating the agent lookup that `resolveTranscriptPath` already does internally. This is a minor efficiency concern but mainly a readability issue -- the callers don't know